Gloster asks, “Tantaene animis caelestibus irae?'’ This saying forms entry No. 391 of the Pramus, and is taken from the AEneid‚ i. 1 1. Peele quotes it in his Speeches to Quem Elizabeth, and it is to be found translated many times in writings of the period, es- pecially in Edmund Spenser, who was fond of it, and in John Lyly. But there is nothing strange about such coincidences, for all writers whom I have read furnish similar material; and for every such case from Shakespeare hundreds could be brought from John Lyly and Ben Jonson.

I do not think, after what I have said, that any good end would be served in pursuing this argument any further.
